SIMPLE: scent
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scent
<hw>Scent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Scented</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scenting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Originally <ets>sent</ets>, fr.
F. <ets>sentir</ets> to feel, to smell. See <er>Sense</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To perceive by the olfactory organs; to smell; <as>as,
to <ex>scent</ex> game, as a hound does</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Methinks I <qex>scent</qex> the morning air.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To imbue or fill with odor; to perfume.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Balm from a silver box distilled around,⟦br⟧
Shall all bedew the roots, and <qex>scent</qex> the sacred ground.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scent
<hw>Scent</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have a smell.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thunderbolts . . . do <qex>scent</qex> strongly of brimstone.</q>
<rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hunt animals by means of the sense of
smell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scent
<hw>Scent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which, issuing from
a body, affects the olfactory organs of animals; odor; smell; <as>as,
the <ex>scent</ex> of an orange, or of a rose; the <ex>scent</ex> of
musk</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With lavish hand diffuses <qex>scents</qex> ambrosial.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically, the odor left by an animal on the
ground in passing over it; <as>as, dogs find or lose the
<ex>scent</ex></as>; hence, course of pursuit; track of
discovery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He gained the observations of innumerable ages, and traveled upon
the same <qex>scent</qex> into Ethiopia.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The power of smelling; the sense of smell; <as>as, a
hound of nice <ex>scent</ex>; to divert the <ex>scent</ex></as>.</def>
<rj><au>I. Watts.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scentful</ent>⟦br⟧
